const week_2 = 
"Everyone in MFADT produces images, lots of themâ€”slide decks for class presentations, image-based work, physical installations, objects, documentation of our projects, social media posts, selfies, sketches, and so on. Making images is for all intents and purposes unavoidable in our communities of practice. And so our focus for week 02: seeing, representation, and power. The concepts covered in Creanâ€™s lecture and the Sturken and Cartwright reading arenâ€™t limited to just images, in the most literal sense. The ideas around meaning-making, normative beliefs, and power dynamics extend, and even expand, when applied to film, music, games, fashion, computation, products, and interaction design writ large.Letâ€™s start with the lecture by Melanie Crean*â€”a longtime full-time faculty member in DT, and former Design for this Century co-faculty. Crean provides an overview of how symbols accrue meaning; how those meanings shift and change over time, place, and cultural context; and the implications of images for our understanding of one another and the world around us. Building upon these ideas are the ways in which the cultural meanings and expectations caused by the interpretation of images exert power over people. The example of the symbol, â€œx,â€  is a case in point: however one interprets that symbol, seeing it focuses a personâ€™s thoughts, in the process shaping and/or controlling (however fleetingly) that personâ€™s attention. Sturken and Cartwright add nuance and detail to many of the ideas presented in Creanâ€™s lecture. The phrase, â€œeconomy of looking,â€ introduced on page 9, is of particular importance. This is one of several uses of the term â€œeconomyâ€ you will encounter in this course that differ from the most common usage relating to  the flow of money. Instead, Sturken and Cartwright use the term to help us think about imagesâ€”their creation, their use, their impactsâ€”as a complex, dynamic system. (We will look at the ideas of systems and systems dynamics week 04.) Semiotics, discussed in both the lecture and the reading, provides an important tool for understanding the dynamic and fluid understanding of images. While the sign itselfâ€”the color red Crean discusses for exampleâ€”doesnâ€™t change, what it signifies, and how it is understood and acted upon, does change. The Marlboro cigarette ads demonstrate how one company sought to manipulate understanding of their product through images celebrating specific imagery to convey gendered messages. This brings us to an important consideration: the ways in which images are used to normalize some ideas, and to exclude other ideas. When something is normalized, it becomes the expected way something is interpretedâ€”if in the US, red means stop, yellow means caution, green means go. It is a quick jump from something being the expected meaning of an image, and people jumping to the conclusion that interpretation is natural or how it is supposed to be. While this is sometimes a good thing (traffic signals), it is also a tool for controlling and excluding and harming. \\";

const week_4 = "Youâ€™ll hear a lot about systems in MFADT, with systems dynamics and systems thinking the two most common phrases. In the most general sense, we use systems to help us understand the complexities of the world, and as a way to understand how we as creative practitioners can intervene into systems in order to effect change. About halfway through Donella Meadowsâ€™ â€œLeverage Points,â€ she provides the essential ideas to grasp systems thinking: â€œstocksâ€ (e.g. the resources) â€œflowâ€ (e.g. move) through a system, in the process creating a systemâ€™s â€œstate.â€ Inflows increase the quantity of a given stock, while outflows decrease the quantity of a given stock. This sounds really straightforwardâ€”and it is, pretty much, if you are talking about a bathtub or another visible, simple system. But most systems in the world are far more complex, and far less visible. In more complex systems, it is not always easy to understand how a system works and what is at stake in that system. Even more complicated is understanding how to effect change (â€œinterveneâ€ in Meadowâ€™s terms).Meadows leverage points introduces a really helpful set of â€œleverage pointsâ€ for effecting change. As she notes, the easier places to intervene are not always the most effective for meaningful change. And the harder places to intervene are the most effective for meaningful change. The Design Studio for Social Interventionâ€™s Ideas Arrangements Effects introduces another approach to systems thinking. Born from their community-based work in Boston, DS4SI shares a model of systems thinking that operates at a more accessible scale for creative practitioners. The two illustrations of classrooms early in the reading (remember, weâ€™re focusing on pages 17-23, with 24-43 for those interested) provides a clear and insightful example of how their ideas, arrangements, effects model can effect change at a realistic scale. One way to think about these two readings: Meadows introduces an analytic framework for understanding a complex system, and DS4SI introduces a practical framework for creatively responding to and working within a complex system. Both are incredibly helpful tools for MFADT (Instruction Sets for Strangers, anyone?). Shifting gears, consider my lecture as a quick introduction to how we think about primary and secondary research here in MFADT. The Major Studio 1 Final Project begins with posing collective questions that you all can build into individual projects, and so we hope this talk helps you think about how to enter the research process. Two points I would like to draw attention to: the ways in which creative research practices interleave primary and secondary research, and the importance of citation. What is probably not clear in the talk is the recursive, iterative, and overlapping nature of creative research. We donâ€™t conduct primary research (e.g. findings you produce) nor secondary research (e.g. findings someone else produces) in a vacuum. With which a project starts really depends on the project and the practitionerâ€”even though we start the MS1 final project with secondary research). And once a creative practitioner has finished a secondary research task, they likely are not done with that sort of research just because they have started making something. The process is fluid, and will inevitably require you loop back and forth between primary and secondary research. The second point I would like to highlight is citation. There is no such thing as original workâ€”everything builds on work done by others. Even if your project is the refutation of a process, tool, idea, or whatever else, it is still beholden to the work the project seeks to replace or improve upon. It is important to acknowledge those whose work yours references, builds upon, refutes, or otherwise makes use of. Citations are how we do this with written work and by extension in presentations (often, in DT, referred to as â€œciting precedentsâ€). \\";

const week_5 ="This week is all about frameworks: for thinking about efficacies in systemic interventions into public health, for understanding the impacts of mediums, and for understanding creative practice. In many ways, these three readings build upon foundations from the last few weeks. They provide examples of using systems thinking to understand complex phenomenon like public health, technologies, and creative practice. At the same time, these frameworks can help us understand and react to the biases and negative impacts of computational technologies raised two weeks ago using the systems thinking tools of Donella Meadows and the Design Studio for Social Intervention we explored last week. Friedanâ€™s health impact pyramid introduces a systems-based model for considering how to intervene into pervasive health issues (consider Friedanâ€™s model to be a fellow traveler to Meadowâ€™s leverage points). Friedan introduces two interlocking ideas. First is the social determinants of health. Borrowing from the World Health Organization, they are income and social protection; education; unemployment and job insecurity; working life conditions; food insecurity; housing, basic amenities and the environment; early childhood development; social inclusion and non-discrimination; structural conflict; and access to affordable health services of decent quality. The second factor Friedan introduces are the actions taken to positively intervene into the health disparities. These include reorienting health services, creating supportive environments, enacting healthy public policy, and strengthening community action. While Friedan focuses on health, his modelâ€”broad societal changes being the most equitable and wide-reaching, and individual interventions being the least equitable and narrowest in reachâ€”can be applied to many other areas in which change is needed. Using Friedanâ€™s terms, we can work to understand the systemic determinants that impact individuals (and the environment, animals, plants, and other inhabitants of the earth), and the actions to more equitably support everyone and everything. Marshall and Eric McLuhan introduce a very different framework, one for making sense of the impacts technologies have on aspects of the world. In the opening examples, the McLuhans use cable television, rear view mirrors in cars, monarchies, and republicanism to model the wide-reaching application of their â€œfour lawsâ€ of technological impact (enhance, obsolesce, retrieve, reverse). As is noted early in the chapter, there is no sequence to the four, and they arenâ€™t equally weighted in their impacts. This framework helps us think through the impacts of new technologies as understood using the broad definition established back in week 01â€”going well beyond computational technologies and instead thinking of technologies as things made by people: languages, tools, computers, math, the scientific process, turntables, etc.). One thing the tetrads framework makes clear: there is no such thing as a new technology that doesnâ€™t impact whomever, wherever, and whatever comes in contact with it. (Starting at page 20, it helps to view the PDF as page spreads rather than as single pages.) Finally, Neri Oxmanâ€™s â€œAge of Entanglement.â€ Oxman proposes a framework for understanding creativity (what she terms â€œcreative exploration, which complements our conception of creative research) as four domains: science, engineering, design, and art. As Oxman notes, these four categories have long been recognized for sure, but as discrete domains with little overlap. Oxman instead suggests that these four creative domains are â€œentangled,â€ or have common concerns and impact one another. In the Krebs Cycle of Creativity, Oxman visualizes these relationships. In this graphic, she introduces a number of additional concepts to organize the four domains. Below the diagram, she provides three models for reading the graphic, and by extension, understanding the entanglement of science, engineering, design, and art. \\";

const model = generateModel(week_5, week_4, week_2);
const output_text = generateText(model);

// document.body.innerHTML = output_text;

// creates a markov chain model based on one or more input strings
function generateModel(...args) {
  const words = args.join(" ").split(" ");
  const model = {};

  // loop through all the words except the last one.
  for (let i = 0; i < words.length - 1; i++) {
    const target_word = words[i];
    const next_word = words[i + 1];

    // if the model doesn't contain the target word, add it.
    if (!model[target_word]) {
      model[target_word] = [];
    }

    // add the next word to the possibilities for target_word
    model[target_word].push(next_word);
  }

  return model;
}

function generateText(model, first_word) {
  // if first_word isn't provided use a random word in the model object
  first_word = first_word || sample(Object.keys(model));

  // start with the word passed in
  let output_text = first_word;
  let current_word = first_word;
  for (let i = 0; i < 120; i++) {
    // choose the next word by sampling from options in the model
    current_word = sample(model[current_word]);

    // append word to output
    output_text += " ";
    output_text += current_word;

    // if we get to a word that ends with "." we are done.
    const last_character = current_word.substr(current_word.length - 1);
    if (last_character === " \\") {
      break;
    }
  }
  return output_text;
}

function sample(array) {
  const index = Math.floor(Math.random() * array.length);
  return array[index];
}


