description:
I manipulated an image of the full color spectrum to show how protanopia, a common form of color blindness, would effect it. This was also an exercise in straight javascript, since I had never used it before. I'm still figuring out how javascript functions and setups differ to the more user-friendly p5.js. Protanopia is red-green color blindness. I tried to effect the pixels in a way that took out the red-green, and with the help of a stack exchange answer I was given the following ratios: 
R Output: R=0.5, G=0.5, B=0.0
G Output: R=0.5, G=0.5, B=0.0
B Output: R=0.0, G=0.0, B=1.0.
Therefore, in the actual code, I did the following:
imgData[i] = imgData[i]/2 + imgData[i+1]/2; 
imgData[i+1] = imgData[i]/2 + imgData[i+1]/2; 
imgData[i+2] = imgData[i+2]; 
imgData[i+3] = imgData[i+3]; 

If I affected one channel too much, It would completely change the whites and blacks even though those should remain normal. In the future, I'd like to improve this - I think the reds and greens can be pulled out more while preserving the luminosity. I would have to figure out how that would correlate to the 4 pixel color channels.

EDIT: Tweaked it more, so the second picture is A LOT better, though it is unfortunately messing with the white. Code is updated below.

